Step3: Model Building¶

In [134]:
# first we need to write our performance measure

performance = function(data, lev, model){
    obs = data$obs # actual default value
    preds = data$pred # predictions
    # this part is added different from the final, because it filters the loans based on instance index which are used in each fold 
    index = data$rowIndex
    loan = data$weights[index]
    two_class = twoClassSummary(data, lev, model)
    for (i in 1:length(obs)){
        if(obs[i]=="Bad"&preds[i]=="Good"){
           x = loan[i]*(-1)
        } else if (obs[i]=="Good"&preds[i]=="Bad"){
           x = loan[i]*0.15*(-1)    
        } else if (obs[i]=="Good"&preds[i]=="Good"){
           x = 0
        } else if (obs[i]=="Bad"&preds[i]=="Bad"){
           x = 0
        }
      cost[[i]] = x  
    }
    customer_cost = do.call(rbind, cost)
    total_cost = colSums(customer_cost, na.rm = T)
    names(total_cost) = "Cost"
    combined = c(two_class, total_cost)
    combined
}

Random Forest¶

In [147]:
set.seed(1)

fitControl = trainControl(method = "repeatedcv",
                        number = n_folds,
                        repeats = n_repeats,
                        classProbs=TRUE, 
                        summaryFunction=performance)

rf_grid = expand.grid(mtry = c(2, 10, 25, 50),
                      splitrule = c("gini", "extratrees"),
                      min.node.size = 5)

rf_fit = train(type ~ ., 
               data = train_smote_balanced[,-c("customer_age", "loan_amount")],
               method = "ranger",
               trControl = fitControl,
               metric = "Cost",
               weights = loans_train,
               tuneGrid = rf_grid)

                tuneLength = 4)

Step7: Conclusion, Comments and Final Comparison¶

By looking at the box plots and comparing the cost metric between different approach, Random Forest still looks like the best algorithm due to its robustness in 5-repeats 10-fold cross validation. So again, it is selected as final method. For furher works one can do the followings:

  • Try to perform dimensionality reduction with PCA or any other method
  • Leverage scaling the data before even though most the models handle this problem
  • Use broader parameter grids.
  • Try other sampling methods like downsampling
